<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Resigned commuters wait to be
impressed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE proposals were greeted by commuters yesterday with a mixture of
resignation, frustration and confusion.
At London's Fenchurch Street station most passengers said they would accept
privatisation if it entailed a better service.
'They can't do a much worse job than they're already doing,' said Mr Lance
Bennet, a junior manager at Sainsbury's, and a regular commuter on the line
to Tilbury and Southend, Essex, dubbed the 'misery line' because of
overcrowding and delays, and one of the candidates for franchising.
Other passengers said the areas that needed improvement and investment were
the quality of rolling stock and punctuality.
'Nothing is ever on time, and they give feeble excuses when it does come,'
grumbled Ms Vicky Thorogood, a bank clerk. Like many others, though, she
admitted that she 'hadn't much clue' about what a franchise actually was.
However, Mr Bill Simpson, a manager who commutes from Barking, Essex, said:
'I'm opposed. I don't think that privatisation is good for the public when
it's heavily weighted against the public.'
</TEXT>
