<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Transporters find some hope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POTENTIAL bidders for passenger franchises found few surprises in Mr
MacGregor's proposals but his plans for freight raised a cheer.
Mr Mike Harvey, spokesman for the Freight on Rail group, which represents
investors in the sector, welcomed Mr MacGregor's announcement as a 'major
positive move' to increase freight on rail.
'Over the last eight weeks or so many of the companies who are already
committed to moving freight by rail have been making sure that MPs and
ministers are aware of how important freight by rail can be to the national
economy. I have to assume that the messages have been getting through.'
The Freight Transport Association, representing large freight users, said it
was delighted with most of the proposals on freight, but 'very concerned'
that while Mr MacGregor announced his intention to raise the gross weight
limit for lorries in joint road/rail haulage operations to 44 tonnes, the
increase would not apply to haulage carried out by road alone. 'There is an
excellent case for 44 tonnes across the board. By restricting it the way he
has, he is almost penalising industry.'
Mr Philip Snowden, managing director of Badger Rail, a division of the bus
operators Badgerline, which is likely to be interested in the Great Western
InterCity line, said: 'We are a bit disappointed that he has restated the
very distinct separation of the authority over the track from the railway
operations.'
He said operation of the track was an important part of the overall service
provided to passengers. 'We would like to have a reasonable degree of at
least day to day control over these aspects.'
But the separation of track and operations was described as 'encouraging' by
Mr Kenneth Irvine, rail privatisation project manager for British Bus, which
is likely to bid for the South West division of Network SouthEast and the
Gatwick Express service.
Mr Keith Taylor, managing director of National Express, the coach operator,
said: 'I welcome the process he has adopted, because it will give
franchisees an opportunity to see what these businesses can produce.'
</TEXT>
