<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / North-south council divide widens: The growing trauma over
criteria for sharing Treasury grants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEBRUARY heralds the annual local government budget trauma. As in past
years, there are daily reports - yesterday from Birmingham - of imminent and
massive cuts in services and staff, blamed on government spending caps and
inadequate Treasury largesse.
With capping far tighter this year than last, the reports could turn into
reality when budgets are finalised next month. But this year's budget round
is novel for the degree of ill-feeling between councils over the criteria
used for sharing out Treasury grants.
Government grants, and capping levels for total spending by each authority,
are based on 'standard spending assessments' (SSAs), calculated each year,
which is the Environment Department's view of the spending needed 'to
provide a standard level of service consistent with (its) view of the
appropriate amount of expenditure for all authorities.' It takes account of
'social, demographic and geographical characteristics'.
It is the way it does so that is causing the fuss. A particular source of
grievance this year is the so-called 'area cost adjustment' (ACA), which is
supposed to compensate councils in the south-east for higher than average
wage costs. But authorities further north say it is an unfair device for
siphoning funds to areas that are already cash rich.
In 1988, the ACA was only Pounds 418m; this year it is Pounds 1.3bn - about
3 per cent of total standard spending (the aggregate of all SSAs) for
England.
Mr Bruce Stevenson, chief executive of Labour-controlled Cleveland, says the
ACA 'has in effect become a redistributive mechanism moving sums of money
from the rest of the world into the south-east.' He described it as 'a
response to a political difficulty' - keeping council tax bills down in
politically-sensitive London.
He claimed that if ACA distributed resources fairly his council would be
Pounds 5m better off - equal to a reduction of Pounds 31 in average council
tax bills.
Shropshire County Council has been leading a national lobby against the ACA.
Though the county, in which no party has overall control, has a Labour
administration, the lobby includes Tory-controlled Hereford and Worcester.
Mr Tony Preece, the county's senior assistant county treasurer, said the
objections to ACA were not political. 'We acknowledge the formula must
reflect the higher costs in London and the south-east, but our reservation
is that the way the formula is applied at the moment more than compensates
authorities in that area.'
Derbyshire County Council, which is also lobbying, points to the rise in its
standard spending assessment compared with that of Hertfordshire, a
beneficiary of ACA. The county treasurer says Derbyshire's SSA rose by 28.9
per cent between 1989 and 1992, whereas Hertfordshire's increased by 43.8
per cent.
Derbyshire and other ACA critics want to see it eliminated for services like
education, police, and the fire service, where pay rates are determined by
national bargaining; and, for other services, to remove private-sector wage
rates as a basis of calculation.
None of that cuts much ice in Hertfordshire, a staunch defender of the
status quo. Mr Bill Ogley, county treasurer says his county 'has among the
highest housing costs in the country, the heaviest traffic and the highest
car ownership.' The Environment Department also insists that the ACA is
intended to reflect real cost differences.
Counties are also united in opposition to metropolitan areas, particularly
London, over rules for calculating standard spending assessments for social
services and 'additional educational needs' - which determine about a fifth
of the education element of government grants to councils.
The grant for additional education depends upon the proportion of an
authority's children living with lone parents, the proportion in families
dependent on income support, and the proportion born outside the UK, US or
Old Commonwealth, or with heads of household born there.
Derbyshire cites research showing there to be 'little if any' relationship
between those factors and the performance of pupils in national tests and
examinations, and thus the real demand for resources in schools. It claims
that the criteria simply channels resources to London and away from county
councils.
When introduced in 1990, SSAs were intended to be a simpler and fairer basis
for distributing government grants to councils than the previous system
comprising 63 components. Alas, in local government simplicity and fairness
are uneasy bedfellows.
</TEXT>
<XX>
