<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Small business welcomes untangling of red tape: Government
takes steps to cut bureaucracy - Insitute of Directors concerned over the
patchy nature of proposed measures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS organisations and owners of small businesses last night welcomed
the government's drive to reduce red tape but said a lot of hard work would
be necessary for it to have any significant impact.
Some were disappointed at the trivial nature of some of the 56 measures
which government departments said they had already taken or were planning to
implement. The Department of Employment, responsible for health and safety
legislation, mentioned steps to remove the regulation specifying the
distance between clothes pegs in changing rooms.
'There are items on the list which are surprising,' said Mr Ian Peters,
deputy director of policy at the Confederation of British Industry. 'If that
is the extent of the lists departments can come up with it demonstrates the
significance of what remains to be done.'
The Forum of Private Business described the programme as 'a good start' but
called for the government to compensate small businesses for the cost of
administering regulations until significant reductions in the burden of red
tape had been made.
The plan to establish seven task forces of businesspeople to re-examine
existing legislation was welcome as long as small businesses were properly
represented. 'We hope small business owners will make up 96 per cent of the
committee members because that is their share of the business community,'
said Mr Stan Mendham, the forum's chief executive.
Ms Jane Lyon, managing director of Clam-Brummer, a manufacturer of
industrial adhesives, said she would welcome the opportunity to sit on the
relevant task force. 'The people who live with the regulations day in, day
out are the people who know the costs they impose on industry,' she said.
Some business owners said they feared that the task forces would be composed
only of 'the great and the good'. I fear it will be a case of the old pals
act,' said Mr Bud Ellis, managing director of Flexi-Pak, a food packaging
company with annual sales of Pounds 1.3m. 'It is absolutely vital that the
little fellow gets a look-in.'
One worry was that the creation of the task forces would put an additional
burden on the business community. 'What is really important is to change the
culture in government so we don't need all these panels,' said Mr Peters.
Of concern to the Institute of Directors was the patchy nature of the list
of actions or proposed actions from the different ministries.
'Some departments have done more than others,' commented Mr Ian Smedley,
responsible for deregulation policy at the institute.
He expressed surprise that no mention had been made of any plan to abolish
or modify the requirement that small companies have their accounts audited
since this was the responsibility of Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs
minister at the Department of Trade and Industry and the junior minister
responsible for the deregulation programme.
Much more needed to be done in the areas of pollution control and health and
safety, while no reference was made to plans to reduce the number of
licences needed to start up in certain business areas, he noted.
The institute said it was pleased to see that the government intended to
link its deregulation programme with the Citizen's Charter. This would
require government departments to promise to respond to requests from
business and the public within agreed time limits.
Mr Smedley said he was also encouraged by the news that the Department of
Social Security was reviewing eliminating the differences between the
definition of earnings for the purposes of PAYE and National Insurance.
Payroll administration is a heavy burden for small businesses and this would
simplify matters, he said.
</TEXT>
