<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Plan for simplified tendering: Defence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Ministry of Defence has a running programme of reforms aimed at cutting
bureaucracy and simplifying procedures for its suppliers.
It announced plans in November to market test each year for the next four
years Pounds 1.2bn worth of services and facilities provided in-house. The
idea is to open up new areas of activity to competition. At the same time, a
fortnightly billing scheme was introduced by the ministry to ensure prompt
payment to contractors. This year the MoD expects to pay more than Pounds
12bn to nearly 20,000 contractors.
Future plans to cut red tape include restricting the number of companies
invited to tender for contracts so that time is not wasted by unsuitable
bidders, reducing price investigations on non-competitive contracts, and
introducing simpler arrangements for the commercial exploitation levy on
products developed for the MoD.
</TEXT>
