<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / House price figures hit hopes for recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES that an upturn in house sales would lead to a swift recovery in prices
were damped yesterday after Halifax, the country's biggest mortgage lender,
reported that house prices on average had fallen by 0.4 per cent in January.
The Halifax's figures conflicted with a survey by Nationwide, the
second-largest building society, which reported that prices on average had
risen by 1.2 per cent last month, the biggest monthly rise since May 1991.
Both societies, however, agreed that there had been an increase in the
number of potential purchasers requesting mortgages and inquiring about
properties for sale.
Halifax said increased activity had yet to feed through to firm mortgage
offers. Nonetheless market activity was expected to show a stronger recovery
by spring, when prices should have started to stabilise.
'There might be some modest monthly increases in the second half of this
year provided that economic confidence generally begins to recover,' said
the society.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, Nationwide's chief executive, said his society's
figures should be taken as an encouraging sign that stability might be
returning to the mar-ket.
He said: 'One swallow does not make a summer, but we believe there are
grounds for cautious optimism. If the latest fall in interest rates helps to
stimulate the economy generally and to boost consumer confidence, a more
active and healthy housing market should emerge.'
The monthly house-price surveys published by Halifax and Nationwide have
occasionally disagreed. Nationwide says this is mainly due to differences
between the societies in what constitutes an 'average house'.
According to Halifax the average price of a home fell by 7.7 per cent to
Pounds 60,471 during the 12 months to the end of January, compared with
Nationwide which estimated the average price of a home last month to be
Pounds 52,507.
Halifax also estimated that the price of a new house had fallen by only 1.9
per cent on average to Pounds 67,060 since January last year.
Mortgage lenders, estate agents and builders have reported a sharp increase
in agreed sales since before Christmas. The Building Societies Association
last week reported the first December increase in mortgage approvals
compared with November for 16 years. Part of the improvement is thought to
be buyers returning to the market after the autumn sterling crisis.
The extent of the damage inflicted on buyers' confidence by wildly
fluctuating interest rates was underlined yesterday by the publication of
mort-gage lending figures for the final three months of last year.
The number of mortgage applications during the fourth quarter fell by 24 per
cent to 173,000 compared with the last three months of 1991, according to
the Council of Mortgage Lenders. Their total value fell by 28 per cent to
Pounds 9.34bn.
Mr Mark Boleat, the council's director-general, said: 'Evidence that
significant falls in mortgage rates were beginning to have a positive effect
on the housing market occurred too late in the quarter to be reflected in
the latest lending figures.'
</TEXT>
