<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Contracting out policies face further trouble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S policies on contracting out public services faces
continuing disruption because of uncertainty over the rights of employees
whose work is contracted out.
Legal advice obtained by the Labour-dominated Association of Metropolitan
Authorities says that the overwhelming majority of contracts put out to
tender by councils are covered by European Community legislation protecting
the jobs and conditions of workers in mergers. This means that the
contractor must take over the employees on their existing terms and
condi-tions, removing scope for savings through lower pay or cutting staff.
The confusion has arisen over the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of
Employment) regulations 1981, which implement the EC's 1977 Acquired Rights
directive.
Recent decisions of the European Court of Justice have extended the scope of
the regulations to cover contracting out of some public services.
However, Mr Patrick Elias, a leading employment QC, has advised the local
authorities associations that the EC directive is likely to apply in most
cases where a service is contracted out.
An amendment to the regulations now passing through parliament will make
this absolutely clear, he says.
Government departments are continuing to suspend plans to put Civil Service
work out to tender until it is clear whether market-testing is covered by
the legislation.
The Home Office has shelved the contracting out of the Prison Service stores
from April 1, following advice that the regulations would apply. The 120
staff employed in the stores had been issued with redundancy notices after
the contract had been won by Beck &amp; Pollitzer, the contract-services group,
in the belief that the regulations did not apply.
The Crown Prosecution Service has shelved plans to put its file store out to
tender while seeking advice from the Treasury solicitor on whether the
regulations apply.
It emerged last week that Mr Michael Bichard, chief executive of the
Benefits Agency, had complained to Sir Michael Partridge, permanent
secretary at the Department of Social Security, over the failure of the
Cabinet Office to answer key questions over the issue. Mr Bichard said that
the lack of clarity threatened agency plans to market-test some 10,000 jobs.
One option for the government would be to seek an amendment of the EC
acquired rights directive to exclude contracting out of public services. The
UK, however, is reluctant to be seen to be pressing too hard for such an
amendment for fear of creating an anti-British coalition against change.
Both Mr Leon Brittan, the EC's external economic affairs commissioner, and
Mr Martin Bangemann, the industry commissioner, have expressed an interest
in an amendment to exclude contracting out in the public sector.
Mr Padraig Flynn, EC social affairs commissioner, has not ruled out such an
amend-ment.
He said recently: 'If it could be shown to me that in special, isolated,
cases, the intention of the law was being defeated in usage then it may
require amendment.'
</TEXT>
