<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Scotland 'not gaining full benefit of multinationals'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH-based companies are failing to fully exploit the opportunities
presented by large multinational electronics companies based in Scotland,
says a new academic study.
As a result inward investment in electronics is not producing as much
benefit to the Scottish economy as it should.
A survey of 106 multinational electronics companies in Scotland by Dr Ivan
Turok of Strathclyde University shows they bought only 12 per cent of the
components and other material inputs from Scottish-based companies. This
percentage is roughly in line with past studies conducted by the Scottish
Development Agency.
Scottish companies tended to supply the multinational plants with simpler
products such as keyboards, plastics, cables, sheet metal, packaging and
printed materials, although Scottish companies were also significant
suppliers of printed circuit boards.
Output by electronics companies located in Scotland rose by an average of 14
per cent a year during the 1980s, reaching Pounds 3.9bn in 1989, while the
output of the rest of Scottish manufacturing industry stagnated, Dr Turok
says.
The value added in Scotland - the locally purchased inputs of material and
labour - declined from 39 per cent of output in 1983 to 24 per cent in 1989.
The relative decline in value added suggests that multinational plants are
increasingly importing components and sub-assemblies from overseas, and
confining their operations in Scotland to final assembly in what are
sometimes called 'screwdriver' operations, Dr Turok says.
Loose Connections? Foreign Investment and Local Linkage in Silicon Glen.
Strathclyde Papers on Planning. 50 Richmond Street, Glasgow G1 1XN. Pounds
4.
</TEXT>
