<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Hoover pays lump sum over controversial deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at Hoover's Cambuslang plant in Glasgow will receive one-off
payments averaging about 20 per cent of annual wages for accepting the
controversial deal on working practices that led to the closure of the US
household appliance manufacturer's factory at Dijon, France.
Every worker will receive Pounds 2,500 as compensation for the end of
restrictive practices and demarcation lines, with a further Pounds 150 as a
goodwill payment. Shift workers will receive Pounds 500 for accepting the
reduction in the three-shift premium rate - the rate paid and calculated per
shift - from 156 per cent to 133 per cent of the basic rate, the industry
average.
Hoover imposed a pay freeze last March and the present agreement will last
until the end of this year. Basic weekly pay rates range between Pounds
169.80 for a labourer to Pounds 212.55 for a craftsman fitter.
Leaders of the AEEU engineering and electricians' union yesterday robustly
defended the deal. 'We have nothing to be ashamed of,' said Mr Jimmy Airlie,
the union's executive officer for Scotland. 'We are not involved in social
dumping. We will be apologising to nobody for what we have done. In the
circumstances it was the best deal we could reach with the company.'
The AEEU points out that many of the jobs lost when Hoover shut its Perivale
plant in west London 10 years ago went to plants on the Continent.
Tomorrow Mr John Weakley, an AEEU executive member not directly involved in
the Cambuslang deal, will meet officials of the European Metalworkers
Federation in Brussels, including a delegation from the CFDT and FO unions
in France.
The federation's executive requested the meeting to discuss the Cambuslang
deal.
Mr Weakley said yesterday he would not be discussing the details of the
deal. 'I will sit down and listen to what they have to say.'
Mr Bill Jordan, AEEU president who also heads the European federation, said:
'Our union will not discuss the content of the agreement - that is our
business. It is not on the table.'
Editorial comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
