FT  03 FEB 93 / Plea over medical research
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW MEASURES are needed to translate advances in medical research into
improved patient care, the government's Advisory Council on Science and
Technology said yesterday.
It identified a 'development gap' in the transfer of Britain's 'world class'
medical research to improved treatments.
It said: 'Frustrated inventors contrast British industry's reluctance to
pick up technology at an early stage, because of the risks involved, with
the enthusiasm shown by US and Japanese manufacturers for new product ideas
and for their willingness to invest for the long-term.'
The council wants the government to set up a Medilink programme to channel
public and private funds towards exploiting ideas from universities and the
National Health Service. It would be an extension of the Link programme of
collaborative research.
