<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Fears on confidentiality prompt industry review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH Bankers Association is conducting an industry-wide review of how
to prevent leaks of customers' account details. The move follows the leak
last autumn to The Sun newspaper of details of Mr Norman Lamont's Access
credit card statement.
Banks are concerned that the leak over the chancellor's details was not
unique, although they dispute claims by some law firms and private detective
agencies that almost anyone's bank account or credit card details can be
obtained relatively easily. Senior bankers said it would be damaging to
business if customers lost confidence in banks' ability to keep their
account details secret.
Mr Brian Pearse, chief executive of Midland Bank, said: 'What I find
concerning is the suggestion that someone will disclose information on bank
customers for as little as Pounds 200.'
Mr Bert Morris, the National Westminster Bank director who called for the
review, said: 'I do not think it is easy to obtain such information. But
there are sophisticated investigators who can get in to our systems.'
The banks' main fear is that some of their employees may be selling
information to private detectives. Because banks have introduced nationwide
computer networks for the storage of customer information, a bank employee
may be able to obtain access to information about any customers of the bank.
Prior to computerisation, the employee could only get access to details
about customers of the branch.
The association's review will cover three issues:
Are there effective legal sanctions against the disclosure of information
about customers' affairs? In particular, is the Data Protection Act tough
enough?
Could banks build more safeguards into their computer systems to make it
harder for employees to use them in unauthorised ways? The process of
'logging on' to a computer system is under particular scrutiny.
Could banks do more to ensure the honesty of their staff?
The law in this area is complex, but lawyers and bankers agree that it is
not a criminal offence to pass on information about a customer's accounts
without authorisation from the customer. It would, however, be a breach of
contract and banks say they would have no hesitation in dismissing an
employee making unauthorised disclosures.
There are laws to protect confidentiality of information stored on computer.
The 1990 Computer Misuse Act makes it illegal for anyone to gain
unauthorised access to computerised information, and the 1984 Data
Protection Act obliges companies to take steps to prevent leaking of
information stored on computers.
</TEXT>
