<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Fifth of passenger rail routes selected for sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PASSENGER services on nearly a fifth of Britain's railway network are likely
to be in private sector hands by the end of next year, the government
announced yesterday.
It also came up with a surprise package of grants and other incentives aimed
at encouraging freight traffic to switch from road to rail.
Grants will in some cases give private sector freight carriers a free ride
on the railway tracks if that is what it takes to persuade them to use rail
instead of roads.
The government also plans to raise maximum lorry weights from 38 tonnes to
44 tonnes for special vehicles which transfer their loads from road to rail
for the larger part of their journey.
The announcements came as Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, defended
the government's controversial rail privatisation plans in the second
reading of the railways bill, which last night received a government
majority of 33.
Mr MacGregor named seven parts of British Rail which will be split from the
network this year and managed autonomously by BR staff on an experimental
basis pending privatisation.
Ranging in size from the Isle of Wight railway to ScotRail, they also
comprise three InterCity routes, East Coast, Great Western and Gatwick
Express, and two Network SouthEast commuter services - the London, Tilbury &amp;
Southend line and the whole of the South West division between London
Waterloo and south-west England.
The government hopes that by preparing these routes for privatisation now,
they can be moved swiftly into private hands after the planned launch of the
privatisation process in April 1994.
Other parts of the passenger railway will take much longer, but Mr MacGregor
said the government's proposals for franchising out the operation of all
BR's passenger services would be mapped out shortly.
The proposals mean that the InterCity network looks likely to be split into
separate franchises. InterCity's management had hoped to bid for the
franchise to operate the network intact. The Department of Transport said it
had not reached any conclusions on the future of InterCity, and that it had
not ruled out the possibility that a single bidder could win more than one
franchise.
The proposals won praise from Sir Bob Reid, BR chairman, who welcomed
measures to boost freight.
Test franchises, Page 15
Letter, Page 22
</TEXT>
