<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / World Stock Markets (America): US blue chips ease as
investors consolidate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
IN SPITE of more good economic news, US share prices were mixed across the
board yesterday as investors consolidated recent gains and searched for
fresh incentives to buy, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 3.51 at 3,328.67. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended 0.03 up at 442.55, another
record close, while the Nasdaq composite gained 3.35 at 705.12. Trading
volume on the New York SE was 271m shares.
After Monday's big advance, the market opened in a cautious mood, with blue
chip prices easing slightly as some investors took the opportunity to book
profits from recent gains. Although the outlook for the economy continues to
brighten, providing underlying support for stock market sentiment,
yesterday's economic figures, although bullish, failed to give shares a
lift.
The day's data consisted of a 1.9 per cent rise in the December leading
index of economic indicators and a 6.3 per cent gain in December new home
sales. Both increases were bigger than analysts had expected, and were
consistent with other recent data which have painted a picture of a
recovering economy.
Equity prices may have been weighed down by the bond market, which suffered
losses across the maturity range yesterday. Recent rises in bond prices have
pushed interest rates to six-year lows, so any reversal in the trend was
likely to lead to a negative reaction from the stock markets.
Individual stocks continued to be affected by fourth-quarter earnings
announcements. Tenneco climbed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 41 7/8 after the
natural gas, and farming and construction equipment manufacturer unveiled
fourth-quarter net income of Dollars 35m, up from Dollars 26m a year
earlier.
Pepsico slipped Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 41 3/4 in busy trading after it
announced fourth-quarter profits of Dollars 265.6m, compared with Dollars
221m at the same stage of 1991. Both sets of figures, however, were affected
by restructuring or accounting charges.
The ADRs in Hanson, the UK-based conglomerate, lost Dollars  1/4 to Dollars
18 7/8 after union workers began a strike at the group's Peabody Coal
subsidiary, the largest coal producer in the US.
Leading drug issues took a beating. Pfizer declined Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars
63 1/8 and Merck Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 37 5/8: both stocks were removed
from the recommended list at Salomon Brothers, the big Wall Street
securities house.
The news depressed the rest of the drugs sector, with Bristol-Myers Squibb
weakening Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 58 1/4, Schering-Plough Dollars 1 1/2 to
Dollars 58 3/4 and Johnson &amp; Johnson Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 43 5/8 .
Colgate-Palmolive rose Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 58 1/4 after it was added to
the Salomon recommended list, on the grounds that the stock has growth
potential.
On the Nasdaq market, Lone Star Steakhouse jumped Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars
41 3/4 in busy trading after the company unveiled plans to accelerate its
rate of new store openings this year. Lone Star also said it was comfortable
with analysts' forecasts that earnings would reach 85 cents a share in 1993.
Canada
TORONTO showed no clear trend after heavy trading. The TSE 300 index was up
10.9 at 3,321.8, but declines held a slight edge over rises by 316 to 305.
Volume amounted to 46.5m shares valued at CDollars 420.9m.
Nine of the 14 stock groups were higher, with the golds sector adding 1.09
per cent.
LAC Minerals, CDollars  3/8 firmer at CDollars 6 1/2 , reported higher
fourth-quarter earnings.
</TEXT>
