<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / Money Markets: Revised expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STERLING cash and futures markets yesterday reined in expectations of
another cut in UK base rates before the March Budget after the UK government
mounted a concerted campaign to restore confidence in the pound, writes
James Blitz.
On Monday, Downing Street denied weekend reports that the prime minister was
about to drive interest rates lower to stimulate economic recovery.
The comments from Mr Major's office had little effect on sterling markets on
Monday, but there was a sharp change of tone to dealing yesterday.
The March short sterling contract dropped 24 basis points in the early part
of the day, falling as low as 94.28, a level which prices three-month money
at Budget time at 5.72 per cent. It only recovered a small amount of lost
ground in the afternoon, finishing at 94.33.
The revised view on rates was also felt in the cash market.
Three-month money closed more or less unchanged at 6 1/4 per cent, helped by
a comparatively small shortage of Pounds 750m forecast by the Bank of
England in the morning.
However, six-month money rose on the bid side by about  1/16 percentage
point to end at 5 7/8 per cent. With the bid rate for one-year money closing
at 5 3/4 per cent, the money market yield curve appeared to be levelling off
yesterday.
A rising yield curve would indicate that dealers believe 5 per cent could be
the eventual floor for base rates in this cycle.
Trading in French franc markets was extremely calm when set against the
volatility of Monday.
The franc barely moved on the foreign exchanges and three-month money fell
back to around 12 1/2 per cent from Monday's 13 per cent. The March French
franc contract climbed 32 basis points, finishing at 85.55, following
Monday's 23-point decline.
The market will scrutinise today's Bundesbank interven-tion in the money
markets for any sign of policy easing, although expectations of this are
low.
There is a heavy call on funds because of the German tax season, and call
money finished a little higher at 8.66 per cent. One money market analyst
was yesterday expecting the lowest accepted repo bid for today to be on the
high side, possibly in the area of 8.61 or 8.62 per cent.
</TEXT>
