<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / International Company News: Posco 27% increase beats
forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POHANG Iron and Steel (Posco), the world's third-largest steel company,
yesterday reported that net earnings for 1992 rose by 27 per cent to
Won185.1bn (Dollars 230m).
The South Korean group's result was better than expected. Analysts had
predicted profits of Won150bn, while its own forecast was Won169bn.
Sales totalled Won6,180bn, an increase of 6 per cent.
Profits were boosted by a rationalisation programme to cut production costs
by Won160bn, increased sales of higher-valued steel products, and a fall in
raw material prices.
Analysts predict that Posco earnings could climb to Won220bn this year as
its capital costs shrink following the completion last year of its fourth
and final steel plant.
Posco, however, could have its exports to the US curtailed if Washington
decides to impose dumping duties in June. Its main export to the US is
hot-rolled steel sheets, which face a 30 per cent dumping penalty. The steel
is mainly delivered to UPI, a California-based 50-50 joint venture of Posco
and USX.
</TEXT>
