FT  03 FEB 93 / International Company News: Reebok profits unchanged in
fourth quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REEBOK International, the US sports shoe maker, yesterday announced
fourth-quarter profits from continuing operations of Dollars 49.8m,
unchanged from a year earlier.
However, the company took a previously-announced restructuring charge of
Dollars 135m in the final quarter which, along with a one-off gain of
Dollars 18m from the sale of stock in CML Group, left Reebok with a net loss
of Dollars 67.6m for the last three months of 1992.
For 1992, earnings before charges and special gains totalled Dollars 232.3m,
down slightly from the Dollars 234.7m earned in 1991.
Mr Paul Fireman, chairman and chief executive of Reebok, said he was pleased
with the company's overall performance in the fourth quarter, citing
increased sales of its Reebok brand both in the US and abroad, of its sports
apparel, and of its Rockport products.
However, sales of the Avia brand, fell 21 per cent in the quarter.
