<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 93 / International Company News: Tapie close to selling his stake
in Adidas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR BERNARD Tapie, the controversial French industrialist and politician, is
on the verge of concluding a deal to sell his controlling stake in Adidas,
the German sporting goods group, to a consortium of investors led by Mr
Robert Louis-Dreyfus, chief executive of the Saatchi &amp; Saatchi advertising
group.
The consortium, which also includes Credit Lyonnais, the French bank, and
Assurances Generales de France (AGF), the insurance company, is expected
within the next few days to finalise negotiations to buy Mr Tapie's 78 per
cent stake in BTF, the German holding company that owns 95 per cent of
Adidas, according to a report in that appears in today's edition of Les
Echos, the French financial newspaper.
Mr Tapie, who recently returned to the French cabinet following the collapse
of a fraud case, has for months been trying to sell his Adidas stake to
reduce the debts of Bernard Tapie Finance, his holding company.
An earlier attempt to sell the stake to Pentland, the UK consumer products
company, collapsed last year.
Last autumn, Mr Tapie instructed Credit Lyonnais to sell the BTF shares for
FFr2.08bn.
Les Echos suggests that Credit Lyonnais, AGF and Banque Worms, another
French bank, will raise their current combined 20 per cent stake in BTF with
Mr Louis-Dreyfus taking between 3 per cent and 7 per cent of the shares.
Mr Louis-Dreyfus, the heir to a French banking fortune, made his name in the
business world as chief executive of Saatchi where he orchestrated a
financial restructuring that saved the group from collapse. He announced
last year that he was leaving Saatchi in mid-1993 to pursue new interests.
</TEXT>
