<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / International Company News: IBM debut in parallel processing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines, the US computer company reeling from
declining sales in its key mainframe market, is today expected to unveil its
first machine using parallel processing, a relatively new technology which
could help shore up its mainframe revenues.
The company is due to hold a news conference to discuss a new scalable
parallel processing system and enhancements to its existing family of
RISC-based (reduced instruction set computing) workstations.
Parallel processing involves using a multitude of off-the-shelf
microprocessors to solve problems.
Traditional mainframes use a few, very fast and very expensive processors.
Parallel processing, which offers buyers much cheaper computing power, has
already been introduced commercially by companies such as Hewlett-Packard
and NRC.
IBM will follow up this announcement on February 9 by unveiling enhancements
to its ES/9000 mainframe line.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>International Business Machines Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  USA.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
