<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Cambodia fighting erupts again: Government attacks against
Khmer Rouge inflict further damage on UN credibility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PHNOM PENH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CAMBODIAN government forces have launched an offensive against Khmer Rouge
guerrillas on several fronts in the worst fighting since the United Nations
peacekeeping mission was established a year ago.
The UN Transitional Authority in Cambodia (Untac) yesterday announced a
catalogue of ceasefire violations since Friday in five of the 11 military
sectors into which the UN has divided the country, including exchanges of
artillery and mortar fire.
Although the ceasefire has been in tatters for months, and there were no
immediate reports of heavy casualties, the offensive will inflict further
damage on Untac's credibility as it attempts to prepare for elections in
May.
Untac officials said villagers in some areas had fled their homes and
government troops had conscripted civilians and former refugees recently
repatriated from Thailand. Some were reportedly being used as forced labour
to carry ammunition, a practice previously associated with the Khmer Rouge
and the military junta in Burma.
The Khmer Rouge had almost from the start refused to co-operate with Untac,
participate in elections or abide by the peace agreements it signed in 1991,
forcing the UN to acknowledge that the existing administration of Mr Hun
Sen, the prime minister, had the right to defend itself.
Yesterday, however, Untac said the latest government offensive could not be
justified by concerns about security.
Officials of the Vietnamese-installed Cambodian government, many of them
corrupt and unpopular, are worried about their likely performance in the
elections and are probably mounting the offensive in an attempt to
strengthen their grip on the countryside. This would give them a stronger
hand in any negotiations to form a coalition after the elections.
Khmer Rouge leaders are boycotting the polls but are banking on being
included in a future administration by Cambodian politicians who will want
to avoid the permanent partitioning of the country into Khmer Rouge and
government zones.
Among other attacks, government forces in the west have advanced to within
20km of Pailin, the Khmer Rouge headquarters near the border with Thailand.
Further incidents were reported from a swathe of territory in the north and
north-east of Cambodia. Troops of Funcinpec, the royalist party, were
involved in at least one clash, but most of the fighting was between the
government and the Khmer Rouge.
The Khmer Rouge was blamed for the deaths of 1m Cambodians during its reign
of terror between 1975 and 1978, when Vietnam invaded and installed a new,
pro-Vietnamese communist government.
UN military observers and electoral workers have often been impressed with
the commitment and discipline of the Khmer Rouge troops they have
encountered, and Untac officials have therefore been surprised by the
success of recent government offensives.
However, there have been signs of differences within Khmer Rouge ranks. Some
Khmer Rouge guerrillas have registered to vote. According to a senior Untac
officer, at least one Khmer Rouge commander refused to join in a previous
battle for the defence of Pailin a few weeks ago.
</TEXT>
