FT  02 FEB 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISION
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
People who prefer pandas will want to see the latest episode of The Ark (BBC
2, 9.25). Waving a bouquet of withered bamboo at her fans, Ming Ming arrives
at the crumbling establishment in Regent's Park, at the same time that other
animals are being crated up and shiped out. Whether one likes zoos or
loathes them, it remains the case that director Molly Dineen has produced an
inventive, well-crafted film dealing with what may well be the last days of
London Zoo.
If you missed My Beautiful Laundrette (C4, 10.00), now is the night to catch
a thoughtful and highly atmospheric film which gives a memorable picture of
London. Tonight sees the last episode of Europe means Business: The
Apprentices of Dresden (BBC2, 5.00), the worthwhile series revealing the
cogs of business live in united Germany. The apprentices in question are of
the Dresdner Bank, opening new branches in the former East where savings
accounts used to pay only 3.25 per cent and personal accounts were unknown.
Out of Sight, Out of Mind in the First Tuesday series (ITV, 10.40) goes over
familiar territory for the socially-concerned film-maker.
</TEXT>
