FT  02 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Magazine regrets 'distress' to PM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW STATESMAN and Society, the left-wing magazine being sued by Mr John
Major over an article in last week's issue, said in a statement yesterday
that it 'very much regretted' any distress caused to the prime minister.
Similar letters went to Mr Major's solicitors and those acting for Ms Clare
Latimer, also referred to in the article, and who is also suing the
magazine. The letters conclude: 'Just as speedily as the litigation was
commenced so we now hope that litigation can be speedily brought to an end.'
The New Statesman's considered reply from its lawyers says the article 'was
intended to be a serious and responsible criticism of the Press generally
for conducting a whispering campaign based on rumours which, when
investigated by the Press, had been found to be totally unsupported by any
evidence.
'That clearly was a comment on a matter of public interest since the
rumour-mongering and whispering campaign involved the Prime Minister.
'The article was never intended to assert that an affair, let alone an
adulterous relationship, had ever taken place between the Prime Min ister
and Ms Clare Latimer.'
It points out that the writs were issued and served before there was any
chance for the magazine to put the record straight in a formal statement and
says it will make any other public statement that might be needed to
vindicate Mr Major's and Ms Latimer's reputations. These views will be
repeated prominently in this week's New Statesman.
