<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Rail sell-off poses royal train
problem
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A QUESTION mark has been put over the future arrangements for running the
royal train as a result of the government's plans for privatising British
Rail.
Department of Transport officials are discussing with Buckingham Palace what
would happen to the train once the planned new regime of a track authority
and franchise-holders operating services is in place. At present the train
is run by British Rail.
Ministers are confident that a deal securing the train's access to track can
be agreed, given the prestige of the service. But the difficulty highlights
the question of charges that will have to be paid to the track authority by
anyone wanting to run a specialist service on the main network.
If there are several franchisees running regional services, arranging for
the royal train to run through a number of regions - for example from London
to Balmoral - would be more complex than now.
MPs are increasingly concerned with the cost of the royal family and the
issue is likely to arise in parliamentary debate of the privatisation. In
1990-91 official royal family travel by train, including royal train
maintenance, cost Pounds 1.4bn, while the royal train renewal programme cost
Pounds 850,000.
</TEXT>
