<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Plasterboard prices about to rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRICES of plasterboard widely used in construction and home improvements are
about to rise for the second time in eight months.
The move is likely to increase builders' fears of further increases for
materials as the economy recovers.
Contractors that have taken jobs at fixed prices simply to cover overheads
could face damaging losses if the cost of materials rose during the work.
British Steel and Pilkington, which supply large amounts of steel and glass
for construction, have announced price increases in the past three weeks.
Prices of some imported timber used in construction have also risen after
sterling's devaluation.
BPB Industries, Europe's biggest plasterboard producer, has told customers
it will raise the prices of some products by more than 10 per cent from the
beginning of next month.
Last summer the company increased prices by an average of about 15 per cent.
The move followed the ending of a bitter European price war between the
three largest manufacturers: BPB, Lafarge Coppee of France and Knauf of
Germany.
Plasterboard prices in France have risen by about a quarter and in Germany
by about 15 per cent since the beginning of last year.
The increases prompted allegations by builders, rejected by the Office of
Fair Trading, that the three companies had colluded over pricing.
Mr John Maxwell, BPB's chief executive, said the company was justified in
trying to recover a small part of its lost margins. He said: 'UK
plasterboard prices fell by more than half in real terms between 1987 and
1992.'
Lafarge and Knauf, which with BPB supply almost all the plasterboard in the
UK, are also expected to raise their prices again following BPB's latest
lead.
Contractors said they will try to resist price increases announced by
Pilkington and British Steel by turning to overseas suppliers if necessary.
Mr Allan Collins, president of the British Constructional Steelwork
Association, said he believed the increases would stick. He said British
Steel was prepared to supply smaller consignments, cut to the finer
tolerances that customers required and competitors found difficult to match.
Prices to constructional steel suppliers are due to rise by 7 per cent to 13
per cent from the end of this month.
</TEXT>
