<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / ITC will consider separate city TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Independent Television Commission will examine the possibility of
starting a series of city television channels on Channel 5 now that plans
for a national network have been rejected.
The study will be part of an ITC assessment on what to do about Channel 5
after the rejection of the only application to run the national network. It
came from Channel 5 Holdings, a venture backed by Thames Television and Time
Warner.
The original plan drawn up with the Department of Trade and Industry was to
use 33 transmitters, allowing 74 per cent of the population to receive the
channel. The winner of the franchise would have had to pay for the re-tuning
of millions of video recorders.
The ITC will examine using different frequencies, removing the need for most
re-tuning.
The frequencies are those once considered for a sixth national channel,
which was rejected because it would have reached no more than 40 per cent of
the population. The ITC will study whether these frequencies could provide
more scope for city stations.
The 1990 Broadcasting Act would have to be amended to allow separate
licences for city-based services on Channel 5 rather than a single national
licence.
The ITC is expected to spend several months on a technical review and
publish a consultative document on future options for Channel 5 later this
year.
Thames was last night considering the ITC statement. The company has not yet
ruled out seeking a judicial review of the rejection of the Channel 5 bid.
</TEXT>
