<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Call for textile training boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEXTILE and clothing comp-anies should invest more in training managers,
says Lancaster University's textile industry research group.
Training systems in textiles and clothing are better organised in Germany,
Italy and France, it says in a report. Training provision in Britain is
closer to the poorly co-ordinated systems in Greece, Portugal and Spain. Dr
Roger Penn, one of the authors of the report, criticised the 'lack of
effective training'.
The report's recommendations include:
Greater investment in training management. 'The textile industry needs to
accept that training does not end once professional and technical
qualifications in textiles have been attained.'
Better co-ordination between employers and education and training
institutions. The Department of Trade and Industry should take a lead. A
modification of pay to reflect individuals' training development. Unions
could take a lead by insisting that such issues became integral to
collective bargaining.
The industry is concentrated in north-west England, the east Midlands, the
Scottish borders and Ulster.
Training in the Textile and Clothing Industries. Textile Industry Research
Group, 27 Shire Road, Silverdale, Carnforth, Lancs LA5 0TB. Pounds 100.
