<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / How banks can dodge obstacles to a 'warm sell': The data
protection registrar's growing concern
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISCLOSURE of Mr Norman Lamont's credit card details in The Sun in December
was a temporary embarrassment for National Westminster Bank, which issued
the card. But banks may regret for a long time having interested the data
protection registrar in how they use personal customer information on
databases.
Mr John Lamidey, assistant registrar with responsibility for financial
services, has become worried by several aspects of how banks use customer
data. He believes they may not only be evading their own code of practice
introduced last March, but could also be breaking the 1984 Data Protection
Act.
Mr Lamidey's intervention on behalf of Mr Eric Howe, the data protection
registrar, comes at an awkward time for banks. They have grown increasingly
interested in using the details they hold about customers' current and
savings accounts to sell them other products from insurance to holidays.
This is becoming more important for high street banks as they try to raise
other forms of income to compensate for losses on bad lending in the late
1980s. Banks are making large investments in insurance subsidiaries in the
hope of being able to 'warm sell' to existing customers.
The potential conflict between confidentiality of customer information and
banks' efforts to sell a wider variety of products was recognised in the
code of practice adopted by the banks.
This says banks and building societies will observe 'a strict duty of
confidentiality'.
Specifically, the code says that banks will not disclose details of accounts
or names and addresses to third parties - including other companies within
the group - except in tightly controlled circumstances. One is where
disclosure is made 'at the request, or with the consent, of the customer'.
Banks have paid less attention until now to the fact that the Data
Protection Act also imposes controls. This is likely to become more
important as banks make use of 'relational databases' which calculate from
personal and account details what sort of products might interest a
customer.
The eight 'data protection principles' say that companies should take
'appropriate security measures' to protect the data they collect and should
also obtain and process data 'fairly and lawfully'.
Mr Lamidey has started to question whether they are complying with the
second requirement.
The situation was summed up neatly in a recent report by Smith New Court,
the firm of stockbrokers, which pointed out that the code was 'an obstacle'
for Black Horse Financial Services - Lloyds Bank's insurance sales
subsidiary. Mr Lamidey is worried about two ways around the 'obstacle'.
The first is that while banks may not directly disclose names and addresses
of customers who they think are interested in insurance to their own
subsidiary, they may send out a mail shot on behalf of the subsidiary to
each customer.
The second is that banks may make it difficult for customers to avoid giving
consent to the broad use of data by asking them to sign their consent as a
condition of getting a particular financial service.
He cites a clause now inserted in forms for Barclays products such as
Barclaycard and Barclays Holiday Club.
Mr Lamidey thinks that a bank may not be obtaining data fairly if it makes
the wider use of data a condition of gaining a service.
It may not even be acting fairly if it makes it hard for the customer to
refuse consent for other uses - for example by insisting on a separate
letter.
An example of what concerns him is Barclays' application form for a personal
loan. It gives the bank permission to use all customer details on its
central information system unless the customer writes a separate letter to
his or her own branch giving account details.
Lloyds Bank wrote to all customers earlier this year asking them to give
express consent for names and addresses to be passed on to its sales
subsidiaries. But application forms for some products now tell people that
they will be sent other marketing material - without a choice being offered.
Mr Lamidey wants to meet banks to discuss such issues. Whatever the outcome,
it is clear that in future banks are likely to face far wider monitoring of
how they use data. Mr Lamidey is already asking questions about whether
customers of telephone banks are adequately protected.
</TEXT>
