<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Save &amp; Prosper to end free banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROBERT FLEMING Save &amp; Prosper is expected to announce today that it is
introducing some transaction charges for banking customers whose accounts
remain in credit. Reaction to the move is likely to be watched closely by
other banks.
The bank, which has about 50,000 customers, said yesterday that it could not
comment on its plans. However, it expected to make an announcement today
which would affect the terms for some of its current accounts.
Mr Ian Lindsey, the group's banking director, said that the bank wanted to
inform its customers first of any changes to their accounts. It had about
six different forms of account with different terms and conditions.
The group was among the financial services groups which introduced free
banking for customers in credit in the 1980s as competition between building
societies and banks for personal customers' business grew.
The large high street banks are all considering introducing charges for
customers in credit, but none has disclosed any immediate plans to do this.
Most banks only charge when personal customers' accounts are overdrawn.
A study by the Association of Payment and Clearing Services found that the
clearing system cost the banks Pounds 4.5bn a year.
