<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / UK Economy: Clarke cool on ERM prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, said last night that the government
was unlikely to consider rejoining the European exchange rate mechanism 'for
some considerable time'.
He said on BBC's Newsnight programme that 'recent events put off rather than
bring forward the prospects of our going into the ERM.
'Right now, obviously, I think everybody can see that not only have we left
the ERM but there is no immediately foreseeable prospect of our going back
in, because the ERM itself is in a very uncertain state.
'Britain rejoining the ERM is not an option we are looking at at the
moment,' he continued. 'It does not seem to me very likely we will be
looking at it for quite some considerable time. There would have to be some
reform before we went back into anything like the ERM.'
The home secretary added: 'Actually, I think we are doing rather well
outside the ERM. The turmoil which is affecting some of these markets is
having a less adverse effect on Britain so far, and by and large we have
successfully managed a reduction of our interest rates to the lowest in
western Europe.'
Mr Clarke also played down any rift between the prime minister and the
chancellor of the exchequer.
'Whenever I meet them, they seem to be working very closely together and to
be on extremely good terms, and have a very clear idea of what they are
doing,' he said.
In the Commons earlier, Tory and Labour backbenchers attempted
unsuccessfully to halt the debate on the measure giving legal effect to the
Maastricht treaty on the grounds that after the devaluation of the Irish
punt the exchange rate mechanism was in effect dead.
