FT  02 FEB 93 / Miners call strike at Peabody Coal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PEABODY COAL, the largest coal producer in the US and a subsidiary of the
UK-based conglomerate Hanson, faces a strike by all 7,700 of its miners
today after union leaders last night called for industrial action over what
it claims are unfair labour practices.
Mr Richard Trumka, president of the United Mine Workers of America, said
that the strike would initially be limited to Peabody, but could be extended
to mines owned by other members of the employers' trade body, the Bituminous
Coal Operators Association, if the BCOA continued to refuse to negotiate a
wage agreement with the unions.
Talks between the unions and employers started on November 6, but the UMWA
claims that since then the BCOA has made no serious attempt to reach
agreement. Mr Trumka said that Peabody and other BCOA affiliates had
'refused to respond to even the most simple information requests' from the
union. The union called for miners to stop work at Peabody from midnight
last night, when the 1988 wage agreement expired.
Mr B R Brown, the chief negotiator for the BCOA, said last night: 'We were
unable to discuss any issues of substance because the United Mine Workers
union raised procedural objections and made take-it-or-leave-it demands,
refusing to talk unless the BOAC agreed to those demands.'
A prolonged strike at Peabody would be extremely damaging for the company,
and its parent, Hanson. In 1991 Peabody produced about 92m tons of coal from
71 mines, generating sales of about Dollars 1.7bn. Only Hanson's tobacco
interests make more money for the parent group than Peabody, which reported
net income of Dollars 263.5m in 1991, 13 per cent of Hanson's total profits.
</TEXT>
