<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Rabin faces up to impasse on deportees: Decision by Israeli
PM amounts to big reversal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE announcement by Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin last night that
Israel will take back 100 of the 400 Palestinians it dumped unceremoniously
on a bleak Lebanese hillside in mid-December was his first public
acknowledgment that the expulsions had, in international terms at least,
seriously backfired.
There is no guarantee that the steps announced by Mr Rabin will resolve
either the immediate plight of the stranded deportees, who are likely to
reject them as inadequate, or the threat hanging over the Middle East peace
talks. But they amount to a significant reversal by Mr Rabin.
Since, in his dual role of prime minister and defence minister, he virtually
bounced his Labour-led government into approving the controversial
expulsions, many ministers had let it be known they felt the decision was a
serious miscalculation from which some diplomatic escape should be sought.
However Mr Rabin continued to insist, in his characteristic growl, that
there was no going back on what he said was a decisive blow against Islamic
fundamentalists waging a violent campaign in Israel and the occupied
territories against the Middle East peace process. He was buoyed by the
unanimous approval of the expulsions handed down by the Israeli High Court
last week.
The court decision, however, simply acted as the signal for a veritable
barrage of pressure from the Clinton administration for concessions which
would defuse growing international calls for action by the United Nations
security council to enforce Resolution 799 demanding the immediate
repatriation of the Palestinians.
President Bill Clinton had expressed himself during the election campaign
and through several of his foreign policy appointees to be a good friend of
Israel. But the prospect of having to cast the first US Security Council
veto in more than two years in Israel's favour, and of perhaps seeing the
Middle East peace negotiations expire so soon after taking office, was
clearly not something relished by Mr Clinton or by Mr Warren Christopher,
his secretary of state.
By yesterday, Mr Christopher and Mr William Harrop, the US ambassador in Tel
Aviv, had talked Mr Rabin round to offering a compromise. Mr Rabin said
Israel had to establish 'an infrastructure of understanding' with the new US
president.
Mr Rabin has almost certainly achieved that. Within minutes of his
announcement, Mr Christopher said any further action by the UN against
Israel was unnecessary - even counter-productive. The US has pledged to work
to get all the Arab parties - including the Palestinians - quickly back to
the peace table.
But it was by no means certain that the obstacle the expulsions placed in
the way of the 15-month-old peace talks had been removed. For a start, the
deportees themselves, mostly sympathisers of the Hamas fundamentalist
organisation which opposes the negotiations, said they would accept nothing
short of full implementation of Resolution 799.
This puts the Palestine Liberation Organisation, which backs the talks, in a
difficult position. The secular PLO, to which the Palestinian negotiating
team from the West Bank and Gaza owes allegiance, is a bitter opponent of
Hamas. Many of its leaders may well support a return to negotiations.
But it will be very difficult for them as long as Resolution 799 is not
fully implemented.
Mr Rabin faces another problem among his own people. Israelis overwhelmingly
supported the expulsions, but now the government has been seen to weaken its
stance in the face of international pressure, undermining the perceived
security benefits.
</TEXT>
