<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Italian Socialists promise not to leave coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY'S Socialist Party last night pledged its full support for Prime
Minister Giuliano Amato's shaky four-party coalition.
Party leader Bettino Craxi quashed rumours that the Socialists were
considering withdrawing from the government after a police raid on their
offices last week.
'We have always supported the government,' Mr Craxi said after a crisis
meeting of party leaders. 'We have always opposed and we will continue to
oppose a government crisis which would only hurl us into an abyss.'
If the Socialists pulled out, the government would fall.
Behind the scenes, however, Mr Craxi was earlier reported to have threatened
to leave the coalition. This threat, coupled with the tension in the party
over the fate of Mr Craxi, has obliged Mr Amato to place the plight of his
government above that of his party.
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro has played an important part in encouraging
the prime minister to take this position. On Sunday he pointedly summoned Mr
Amato to the presidential palace.
The extent of Mr Scalfaro's influence in keeping the coalition alive was
also underlined by former president Francesco Cossiga, who observed
yesterday that there was a return to a strong presidency. Mr Amato's
position towards Mr Craxi has been followed by Mr Claudio Martelli, justice
minister, and Mr Carlo Ripa di Meana, environment minister.
Mr Amato, who refused to attend yesterday's meeting, needs all the support
he can muster on Thursday when his government, with only a slim majority,
faces a series of no-confidence motions from opposition parties.
This comes as the coalition risks being undermined by a bitter battle
between Mr Craxi - the prime minister's notional party superior and former
close colleague - and the Italian judiciary.
Mr Craxi has received three separate advisory notes from Milan magistrates
that he is under investigation for alleged corruption and illegal party
financing. Parliament must consider whether to waive his parliamentary
immunity.
He has rejected any suggestion of wrong-doing and has gone on the offensive,
claiming the magistrates are out to undermine Italian democracy. He claims
they have over-stepped their authority in the 11-month-old Milan corruption
scandal and are conducting a campaign of denigration of himself and the
Socialist party.
The mere prospect of a political chaos rattled financial markets on Monday.
Bonds opened sharply lower and failed to recoup, and the lira had slipped on
opening to 934 against the D-Mark from 928 on Friday.
</TEXT>
