<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / Major seeks to restore market faith in sterling: Further
interest rate cuts ruled out - Downing Street denies division over policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, JAMES BLITZ and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday moved to damp expectations of further cuts in UK
interest rates as the government mounted a concerted campaign to restore
confidence in sterling, economic policy and Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor.
With the pound under downward pressure on the foreign exchanges, Downing
Street, the Treasury and the Bank of England sought to reassure markets that
Mr Lamont was in full charge of economic policy and that there were no
splits with the prime minister over interest rates.
Sterling plunged to a historic low of DM2.3550 in yesterday's far east
trading after weekend press reports of a split triggered a sharp burst of
speculative selling.
The pound recovered slightly in London to close at DM2.3800, more than a
pfennig down from last Friday's close. In New York it made further gains,
finishing at DM2.3876.
Measured against the Bank of England's sterling exchange rate index, the
pound ended sharply lower at 77.4. The index, which is monitored by the
chancellor as a guide to the currency's strength, fell to a record low of
77.3 yesterday morning from 78.2 on Friday night.
In a day which saw continuing tensions in the European exchange rate
mechanism following the devaluation of the Irish punt, British economic
policy was assailed by Mr Michel Sapin, the French finance minister.
Mr Sapin criticised the UK for failing in its obligations to the EC.
'Britain has no right to run a policy on the lines of 'I'll try to save
myself and too bad for the rest of you'. Especially as it isn't working,' Mr
Sapin said.
However the UK authorities insisted that last week's one percentage point
cut in bank base rates to 6 per cent was consistent with the government's
target of returning to economic growth with low inflation.
In a speech to the Overseas Bankers' Club in London, Mr Robin
Leigh-Pemberton, the Bank of England governor, said he had supported the
rate cut for this reason.
For the second day running, Downing Street denied weekend reports that Mr
Major was the driving force behind the rate cut and was seeking an eventual
reduction in interest rates to 4 per cent. A Downing Street official said
the decision last week to cut base rates to 6 per cent had been proposed by
Mr Lamont.
Doubts continued, however, among Conservative MPs at Westminster over the
political authority of Mr Lamont amid widespread expectations that he will
be moved by the prime minister after the March 16 Budget.
Speculation about differences between Mr Lamont and Mr Major has been
fuelled by the prime minister's decision to take a closer involvement in
Treasury policy in the run up to the Budget.
The chancellor has long been regarded as more cautious on interest rate
cuts. But government officials suggested that yesterday's developments would
make further rate cuts less likely.
Downing Street said the weekend reports of Mr Major wanting big cuts in the
cost of borrowing had backfired because of their impact on the pound. 'The
one thing that damages the likelihood of interest rate cuts is talking about
interest cuts,' it said.
Separately, aides to Mr Lamont made clear that he does not regard further
cuts in the cost of borrowing as likely before the Budget. 'Interest rates
are as likely to go up next as they are to go down,' they said.
Government officials pointed out that there has already been a substantial
loosening of policy since sterling left the ERM in September and that the
effects of this have still to work through fully to the economy.
The Treasury pointed out that 1m households will gain this month from a
three percentage point fall in mortgage rates that are set annually and that
more households will benefit in this way in the months ahead.
Meanwhile, the government said that it believed the recent turmoil on
currency markets, renewed by the weekend devaluation of the Irish punt, was
strengthening Britain's hand in its attempts to reform the ERM.
