<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow draws strength from NAPM
report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices staged a solid advance yesterday, aided by a bullish
economic report from the National Association of Purchasing Management,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 22.15 higher at 3,332.18 and the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 rose 3.74 to 442.52, while volume on the New York SE
totalled 238.6m shares. The Nasdaq composite appreciated 5.43 to 701.77.
The market opened firmer, buoyed by strong gains in overseas equities,
notably in Tokyo, Frankfurt and London. On a lighter note, analysts were
suggesting that superstitious investors may have been buying stocks
yesterday following the Dallas Cowboys' victory in Sunday's Super Bowl.
History shows that the stock markets do well in the years that follow a win
by a team from the National Football Conferece - the Cowboys are from the
NFC.
Ultimately, however, the market drew its strength from the NAPM's January
report, which showed that its index of manufacturing activity nationwide
climbed from December's 55.4 to 58.0 last month, a bigger improvement than
analysts had forecast. The NAPM figures were just the latest in a string of
reports showing that the economic recovery is picking up pace.
American Express was the day's feature, rising Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 24
3/4 on 6.6m shares traded as investors responded to the unexpected news over
the weekend that Mr Jim Robinson, the company's much-criticised chairman,
had resigned.
Last week the share price fell sharply after Mr Robinson had apparently won
a bitter battle to stay on at the beleaguered travel and financial services
giant. Yesterday, Mr Richard Furlaud, a key member of the board of
directors, was named non-executive chairman.
RJR Nabisco put on Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 8 3/4 in volume of 6.9m shares on
reports that the company is considering issuing a second class of stock
pegged to its food business. RJR may also have been buoyed by an Illinois
court ruling that rejected a smoker's allegation that tobacco companies
deliberately concealed the full dangers of smoking from consumers. News of
the court judgment aided other tobacco stocks.
On the Nasdaq market, Lilly added Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 23 3/4 after
announcing fourth-quarter net income of 39 cents a share, almost double the
20 cents earned a year earlier.
Leading technology stocks, which took a beating from profit-taking last
week, were back in favour. Intel rallied Dollars 4 1/2 to Dollars 111 1/4 as
3.2m shares changed hands. Canada
TORONTO ended on a slightly firmer note after fairly heavy trading. The TSE
300 index gained 5.4 at 3,310.9 and rises led declines by 329 to 310. Volume
came to 37.5m shares.
Canadian Bond Rating Service downgraded certain debt and securities of
several members of the Edper group of companies, citing concern over
earnings and significant share value declines.
Among the stocks affected by the downgrades, Royal Trustco fell 48 cents to
CDollars 1.22, Coscan Development 40 cents to 60 cents, Brascan 'A' CDollars
 5/8 to CDollars 9 3/8 , Trizec 'A' 10 cents to CDollars 1.90 and Trilon
Financial 'A' 55 cents to CDollars 2.15.
